long_desc.thetext: Proposed workaround and a test case committed via http://git.eclipse.org/c/jdt/eclipse.jdt.core.git/commit/?id=56632b66e4460fbaf36da5ee9142d7bce0f56a9e

Created attachment 245722 Screenshot
(In reply to Jayaprakash Arthanareeswaran from comment #3) > Verified for 4.5 M1 with build I20140804-2000 > > A note: After this bug fix, the resulting code looks like this: > > List<Comparable> emptyList = Collections.emptyList(); > method2(emptyList); > > which has compilation error. Is there a bug for this already? Otherwise, I > could create one.
What is the expected resulting code?
Currently, while extracting the local variable, the "Extract Local Variable" wizard shows the compile error and if the user agrees to continue with the error, the variable is extracted. (See attached screenshot)

(In reply to Noopur Gupta from comment #4) > What is the expected resulting code?
Something that doesn't result in a compile error? :)
> Currently, while extracting the local variable, the "Extract Local Variable" > wizard shows the compile error and if the user agrees to continue with the > error, the variable is extracted. (See attached screenshot)
I knew you would say that. And I agree that we can't possibly 'extract' in a way that compiles. My question is, is this what is usually done in UI for cases where refactor results in errors? Or there other alternatives?

The UI usually shows an error message but doesn't block the user from proceeding. We could try to come up with a custom message that explains the problem in more details, but I don't think that's necessary for this very special situation. Nothing more to do on the UI side.
